\section{Limitation of the approximation}
\subsection{Accuracy}
The function $\phi(x)$ are normally use for probability density function(PDF) which is strictly in the range
\[
0\le P(X)\le1
\]
And error of $0.1$ can cause big error as it is a integral which calculate the area below the curve and it could cause error that mislead the decision making. For example in this question:

The random variable $X$ follows a normal distribution of $X\sim N(0,1)$, find $P(0.1\le X \le 1)$.

If we use the approximation, $P(0.1\le X \le 1)$ will be
\[
\int_{0.1}^1\frac{\sin(x\sqrt{3})}{x\sqrt{6\pi}}dx=0.2983...
\]
while the true value is 
\[
P(0.1\le X \le 1)=0.30151.....
\]
which is small but will affect strict calculation where error allowed is small.
\subsection{Complexity of function}
The function $\frac{\sin(x\sqrt{3})}{x\sqrt{6\pi}}$ do not have a ordinary integral solve, which make it also hard to integrate, however, using u-sub, we could integrate it with the Sine Integral function which ain't normally in a scientific calculator, making the use of the approximation not big. Also, because the approximation has the domain $x\ne 0$, making any calculation with $x=0$ improper integral. In addition, some interval might give out negative value which mean nothing in probability.
\section{Conclusion}
This approximation provide a great alternative to the standard normal distribution function which is simpler with a not big error. Also it could explain the relationship between SND and binominal distribution which is often taught in textbook. However, the approximation is not as useful as it has the maximum error of 0.1 and it require the sine integral function to calculate. Anyway this is a pretty unique and fun approximation.
\section{Mathematic appendix}
\subsection{Finding the best scale factor for horizontal}
\label{app:math} 
\hypertarget{app:math}{} % 
using Taylor expansion, we could expand $\phi(x)$ and $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}C(kx)$ where $k$ is a real number to
\[
\phi(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}(1-\frac{x^2}{2}+\frac{x^4}{8}-\frac{x^6}{48}.......)
\]
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}C(kx)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\left(1-\frac{\pi^2k^2x^2}{6}+\frac{\pi^4k^4x^4}{120}+\cdots\right)
\]
As the first unequal term, which is the coefficient of $x^2$ will affect the accuracy by the most, we would equalize the coefficient of them.
\[
\frac{x^2}{2}=\frac{\pi^2k^2x^2}{6}
\]
then
\[
\frac{1}{2}=\frac{\pi^2k^2}{6}
\]
\[
k^2=\frac{3}{\pi^2}
\]
\[
k=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\pi}=c
\]
so $c$ is the best coefficient of $C(kx)$
